1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,700
Dictionaries are yet another data type in

2

00:00:02,700  -->  00:00:05,980
Python that you'll come to know and use regularly.

3

00:00:05,980  -->  00:00:08,620
Imagine you're running a library and need to track

4

00:00:08,620  -->  00:00:11,480
which books belong to which genre or topic,

5

00:00:11,480  -->  00:00:16,880
or which authors have written specific books in your collection of books.

6

00:00:16,880  -->  00:00:19,380
The library is huge after all,

7

00:00:19,380  -->  00:00:24,280
and you don't have time to count through every single book. You'd be there forever.

8

00:00:24,280  -->  00:00:28,200
How would you organize all of this data efficiently?

9

00:00:28,200  -->  00:00:30,440
This is where dictionaries come in,

10

00:00:30,440  -->  00:00:31,860
and fortunately, for us,

11

00:00:31,860  -->  00:00:36,845
Python has a very unique way of storing data that we call key-value pairs.

12

00:00:36,845  -->  00:00:40,050
Dictionaries allow you to associate data,

13

00:00:40,050  -->  00:00:45,150
like matching up book titles with their genres or authors with their own books.

14

00:00:45,150  -->  00:00:48,370
Let's look at an example of a dictionary like this.

15

00:00:48,370  -->  00:00:51,550
Here, the keys are the book titles,

16

00:00:51,550  -->  00:00:55,590
and the values are the genres associated with the books.

17

00:00:55,590  -->  00:00:57,990
Thanks to this handy data structure,

18

00:00:57,990  -->  00:01:01,630
we can use the book title key to look up or unlock

19

00:01:01,630  -->  00:01:06,490
the genre value that the book is associated with.
